<span class="displaytext"><b><em>"senator (candidate last) has a troubling history of neglecting substantive issues and getting personal in his attacks against those who happen to disagree with him. it's the (candidate last) way."</em> – (candidate last) spokesman kevin madden</b> <p><br/> <b> <u>sen. (candidate last) cannot explain his positions, and so he launches negative personal attacks:</u> </b> </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last) can't address criticism of his tax and immigration policies because he "has no good response."</b> "both responses by (candidate last) have this in common -- they fail entirely to address the substance of (candidate last)'s criticism. the reason, of course, is that (candidate last) has no good response. he did oppose tax cuts, support for which does lie at the essence of reagan conservatism. similarly, he did support comprehensive immigration reform and his line on that support now is a grudging acknowledgement that the american people (though not necessarily (candidate last)) want border security first." (paul mirengoff, "(candidate last)'s point," power line blog, <a href="http://www.powerlineblog.com/archives2/2007/12/019386.php">http://www.powerlineblog.com/</a>, posted 12/27/07) </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last) complains that discussing policy positions is "attacking."</b> sen. (candidate full): "if there's any doubt that we're doing well, it's when (candidate full) starts attacking." (<em>national review</em> online, posted 12/28/07) </p><p><b>and now, sen. (candidate last) has launched a negative personal attack on gov. (candidate last).</b> "'i begin the ad by indicating he's an honorable man,' mr. (candidate last) said. 'i believe he is a good person. i make no attacks on his character, no attacks of a personal nature whatsoever. i've just seen the text of his ad. it's obviously of a very different nature. it's an attack ad. it attacks me personally. it's nasty. it's mean-spirited. frankly, it tells you more about senator (candidate last) than it does about me that he'd run an ad like that.'" (marc santora, "(candidate last) ad: right back at ya, mitt," <em>the new york times</em>' caucus blog, <a href="http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2007/12/28/(candidate last)-ad-right-back-at-ya-mitt/">http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/</a>, posted 12/28/07) </p><p><b> <u>launching negative personal attacks is the (candidate last) way – as seen in the 2000 campaign: <br/></u> </b> <br/> <b>in 2000, sen. (candidate last) ran an attack ad comparing then-gov. bush to bill (candidate last).</b> sen. (candidate last): "i guess it was bound to happen. governor bush's campaign is getting desperate, with a negative ad about me. the fact is, i'll use the surplus money to fix social security, cut your taxes and pay down the debt. governor bush uses all of the surplus for tax cuts, with not one new penny for social security or the debt. his ad twists the truth like (candidate last). we're all pretty tired of that. as president, i'll be conservative and always tell you the truth. no matter what." ((candidate last) 2000, campaign ad, 2/9/00) </p><p align="center"> <em>to watch the 2000 campaign ad, click here:</em> <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uhoxkcprdl4">www.youtube.com/watch?v=uhoxkcprdl4</a> </p><p><b>gov. (candidate last): (candidate last)'s latest attack is reminiscent of the 2000 campaign.</b> "'it's reminiscent of what he did against george w. bush in 2000, which as you recall, he accused president bush of twisting the truth like bill (candidate last),' he said. 'again, this is the kind of nasty, personal attack, which really doesn't have a place in this process.'" (marc santora, "(candidate last) ad: right back at ya, mitt," <em>the new york times</em>' caucus blog, <a href="http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2007/12/28/(candidate last)-ad-right-back-at-ya-mitt/">http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/</a>, posted 12/28/07) </p><p><b> <u>these, on the other hand, are substantive facts – not negative personal attacks:</u> </b> </p><p><b>fact: in 2001, (candidate last) was one of only two (PARTY NAME)s to vote against the $1.35 trillion bush tax cut.</b> the bill lowered marginal rates, eliminated the marriage penalty, and doubled the child tax credit. (h.r. 1836, cq vote #170: adopted 58-33: r 46-2; d 12-31; i 0-0, 5/26/01, (candidate last) voted nay) </p><p><b>fact: in 2003, (candidate last) was one of only three (PARTY NAME)s to twice vote against the $350 billion bush tax cut.</b> the comprehensive bill lowered taxes by $350 billion over 11 years – including increasing the child tax credit and eliminated the marriage penalty. (h.r. 2, cq vote #179: passed 51-49: r 48-3; d 3-45; i 0-1, 5/15/03, (candidate last) voted nay; h.r. 2, cq vote #196: adopted 50-50: r 48-3; d 2-46; i 0-1, 5/23/03, (candidate last) voted nay) </p><p><b>fact: in 2002, (candidate last) was one of only two (PARTY NAME)s to twice vote against permanent repeal of the death tax.</b> (s. 1731, cq vote #28: adopted 56-42: r 45-2; d 11-39; i 0-1, 2/13/02, (candidate last) voted nay, h.r. 8, cq vote #151: motion rejected 54-44: r 45-2; d 9-41; i 0-1, 6/12/02, (candidate last) voted nay) </p><p><b>fact: (candidate last) sponsored an immigration plan to allow 11 million illegals to remain in the u.s.</b> "the (candidate last) plan -- which is being put forward in the u.s. house by arizona gop congressmen jeff flake and jim kolbe -- allows the 11 million illegal immigrants already in the u.s. to stay in the country if they apply for legal status and pay a $2,000 fine." (mike sunnucks, "napolitano, hayworth criticize bush on illegal immigration," <em>the phoenix business journal</em>, 2/1/06) </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p>- <b>rep. steve king (r-ia) called the (candidate last)-kennedy immigration bill "amnesty."</b> "[(candidate last)] has also teamed up with sen. edward m. kennedy (mass.), a liberal (PARTY NAME), on an immigration bill that many conservatives despise. 'it would have legalized and provided a path for citizenship, which is amnesty, for 66.1 million people,' said rep. steve king (r-iowa), who has called kennedy and (candidate last) 'amnesty mercenaries.'" (michael d. shear, "(candidate last) fighting to recapture maverick spirit of 2000 bid," <em>the washington post</em>, 3/15/07) </p><p><b>- manchester <em>union leader</em> editorial: (candidate last)-kennedy proposal "would encourage border jumping."</b> "sens. (candidate full) and ted kennedy have a bill that, surprise, includes a generous guest worker program that would encourage border jumping. illegals who register would have to pay a fine and taxes, but they would get to stay here and apply for permanent residency. that sure beats waiting at the border and hoping to be let in." (editorial, "turnstile security," the [manchester, nh] <em>union leader</em>, 3/27/06) </p></blockquote></span>



